Today, I explored a simple but interesting problem: Checking if a number is a Power of 2!



ğŸ¤” What does "Power of 2" mean?

A number is a power of 2 if you can keep dividing it by 2 until you reach 1, without any remainder.





ğŸ“Œ Examples:

 âœ” 8 â†’ 8 â†’ 4 â†’ 2 â†’ 1 âœ… (Power of 2)

 âœ” 16 â†’ 16 â†’ 8 â†’ 4 â†’ 2 â†’ 1 âœ… (Power of 2)

 âŒ 10 â†’ 10 â†’ 5 (not divisible by 2) âŒ (Not a power of 2)





ğŸ› ï¸ JavaScript Code to Check Power of 2

function isPowerOfTwo(n) {

    if (n < 1) {

        return false;  // Negative numbers & 0 are not power of 2

    }

    while (n > 1) {

        if (n % 2 !== 0) {  // If remainder is not 0, it's not power of 2

            return false;

        }

        n = n / 2;  // Keep dividing by 2

    }

    return true;

}

console.log(isPowerOfTwo(8));  // Output: true

console.log(isPowerOfTwo(10)); // Output: false





â³ Understanding Time Complexity

ğŸ”µ How many times do we divide n by 2?

If n = 8, we divide 3 times â†’ 8 â†’ 4 â†’ 2 â†’ 1

If n = 16, we divide 4 times â†’ 16 â†’ 8 â†’ 4 â†’ 2 â†’ 1

If n = 32, we divide 5 times â†’ 32 â†’ 16 â†’ 8 â†’ 4 â†’ 2 â†’ 1

Since we keep dividing n by 2, the time complexity is O(log n) (Logarithmic Time Complexity).





ğŸ’¡ Simple Takeaways

âœ” Logarithmic time complexity is faster than linear (O(n)).

âœ” Checking power of 2 is useful in memory allocation, game development, and optimization techniques.

âœ” The approach reduces n step-by-step, making it efficient.





